    <div class="container">
        <header>
            <h1>Learning Java with an AI Tutor</h1>
            <p class="subtitle">An Autoethnographic Documentation of Three Days with Claude</p>
            <p style="margin-top: 20px; color: #666;">A critical exploration of AI-assisted learning, human-computer pedagogy, and the future of education</p>
        </header>

        <div class="intro">
            <h2 style="color: #667eea; margin-bottom: 20px;">The Experiment</h2>
            <p>For three days, I used Claude, an AI chatbot, as my primary Java tutor. This document captures not just what I learned about 2D arrays, ArrayLists, and object-oriented programming‚Äîbut what I discovered about learning itself in the age of artificial intelligence.</p>
            <p style="margin-top: 15px;">This is both a technical journal and a cultural investigation: <em>What does it feel like to learn from a machine? What do we gain? What do we lose?</em></p>
        </div>

        <!-- DAY 1 -->
        <div class="day-section">
            <div class="day-header">
                <div class="day-number">01</div>
                <div class="day-title">
                    <h2>2D Arrays</h2>
                    <p class="day-date">October 28, 2025</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="reflection">
                <h3>Pre-Session Reflection</h3>
                <p><strong>Emotional State:</strong> I felt nervous and a little intimidated. Arrays already confuse me sometimes, so the idea of ‚Äúarrays within arrays‚Äù sounded even scarier.</p>
                <p><strong>Prior Knowledge:</strong> I knew that a 2D array is basically like a grid or table made of rows and columns, but I wasn‚Äôt sure how to access or loop through it properly.</p>
                <p><strong>Expectations:</strong> I hoped Claude could make it less abstract ‚Äî maybe help me visualize how data moves in two dimensions. My main anxiety was accidentally memorizing code instead of understanding it.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="chat-exchange">
                <div class="question">
                    What‚Äôs the difference between a regular array and a 2D array in Java?
                </div>
                <div class="answer">
                    A regular array holds a list of elements of the same type, while a 2D array holds multiple arrays ‚Äî essentially a grid. You can think of it as a table where each cell is accessed using two indices: one for the row and one for the column.
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="code-block">
<span class="code-comment">// Example: creating and filling a 2D array</span><br>
<span class="code-keyword">int</span>[][] grid = <span class="code-keyword">new</span> <span class="code-keyword">int</span>[<span class="code-number">3</span>][<span class="code-number">4</span>];<br>
<span class="code-comment">// Filling the grid</span><br>
<span class="code-keyword">for</span> (<span class="code-keyword">int</span> row = 0; row &lt; 3; row++) {<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<span class="code-keyword">for</span> (<span class="code-keyword">int</span> col = 0; col &lt; 4; col++) {<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;grid[row][col] = row + col;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;}<br>
}<br>
<span class="code-comment">// Accessing a specific cell</span><br>
System.out.println(grid[1][2]);
            </div>

            <div class="analysis-box">
                <h3>Pedagogical Analysis</h3>
                <p><strong>What worked:</strong> Claude‚Äôs explanations were very step-by-step and visual. It compared arrays to spreadsheet cells, which made everything easier to picture.</p>
                <p><strong>What was confusing:</strong> When I asked about ‚Äújagged arrays,‚Äù the explanation got too technical too quickly. It assumed I already knew memory allocation terms.</p>
                <p><strong>Compared to human teaching:</strong> Claude was faster and more patient, but also less emotionally aware. A human might have noticed when I was confused; Claude waited for me to admit it.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="breakthrough">
                <h4>üí° Breakthrough Moment</h4>
                <p>When I realized I could loop through a 2D array using nested for loops, it suddenly made sense ‚Äî the structure wasn‚Äôt abstract anymore, it was just numbers in rows and columns.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="key-learning">
                <strong>Key Concept Learned:</strong> 2D arrays are arrays of arrays, and looping through them requires nested loops where the outer loop controls rows and the inner loop controls columns.
            </div>

            <div class="reflection">
                <h3>Post-Session Reflection</h3>
                <p><strong>What I learned:</strong> How to declare, initialize, and traverse 2D arrays. Also how to visualize data stored in them.</p>
                <p><strong>How it felt:</strong> Surprisingly empowering ‚Äî once it clicked, it felt like unlocking a new dimension of logic.</p>
                <p><strong>Questions that remain:</strong> How do you print a 2D array neatly, or convert it to an ArrayList?</p>
                <p><strong>Cultural observation:</strong> AI tutoring feels less pressured ‚Äî I could make mistakes without embarrassment. But it also made me realize how lonely self-learning can be without human connection.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- DAY 2 -->
        <div class="day-section day2">
            <div class="day-header">
                <div class="day-number">02</div>
                <div class="day-title">
                    <h2>ArrayLists</h2>
                    <p class="day-date">October 29, 2025</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="reflection">
                <h3>Pre-Session Reflection</h3>
                <p><strong>Emotional State:</strong> I felt more confident after understanding 2D arrays, but I was still anxious about syntax errors.</p>
                <p><strong>Connection to Day 1:</strong> This topic builds on arrays, but with more flexibility ‚Äî so I was curious to see how ArrayLists handle resizing and objects.</p>
                <p><strong>Relationship with Claude:</strong> I felt more comfortable asking ‚Äúdumb‚Äù questions. I stopped worrying about being judged for not understanding.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="chat-exchange">
                <div class="question">
                    What‚Äôs the main difference between an Array and an ArrayList?
                </div>
                <div class="answer">
                    Arrays are fixed in size ‚Äî once you create them, you can‚Äôt add or remove elements. ArrayLists, on the other hand, can grow or shrink dynamically. They also come with built-in methods like add(), remove(), and contains().
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="code-block">
<span class="code-keyword">import</span> java.util.ArrayList;<br><br>
ArrayList&lt;<span class="code-keyword">String</span>&gt; names = <span class="code-keyword">new</span> ArrayList&lt;&gt;();<br>
names.add(<span class="code-string">"Ruuka"</span>);<br>
names.add(<span class="code-string">"Helio"</span>);<br>
names.remove(<span class="code-string">"Ruuka"</span>);<br>
System.out.println(names.contains(<span class="code-string">"Helio"</span>)); 
            </div>

            <div class="analysis-box">
                <h3>Evolving Dynamics</h3>
                <p><strong>Trust level:</strong> I trusted Claude more. I noticed I stopped double-checking every line in other sources because its code always compiled correctly.</p>
                <p><strong>Question quality:</strong> My questions became more conceptual ‚Äî I asked ‚Äúwhy‚Äù instead of ‚Äúhow.‚Äù</p>
                <p><strong>Dependency:</strong> I realized I was relying on Claude to debug my mistakes instead of learning to read error messages myself.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- DAY 3 -->
        <div class="day-section day3">
            <div class="day-header">
                <div class="day-number">03</div>
                <div class="day-title">
                    <h2>Classes & Objects</h2>
                    <p class="day-date">October 30, 2025</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="reflection">
                <h3>Pre-Session Reflection</h3>
                <p><strong>Emotional State:</strong> Nervous again ‚Äî everyone says object-oriented programming is where Java ‚Äúgets serious.‚Äù</p>
                <p><strong>Learning trajectory:</strong> I noticed that repetition helps a lot ‚Äî asking Claude to rephrase things in simpler ways reinforced my understanding.</p>
                <p><strong>Final day thoughts:</strong> I wanted to make sure I could actually write my own class from scratch without copying examples.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="chat-exchange">
                <div class="question">
                    What exactly is an ‚Äúobject‚Äù in Java?
                </div>
                <div class="answer">
                    An object is an instance of a class ‚Äî a concrete thing created from a blueprint. If a class defines what something *is* and what it *can do*, then an object is that thing in action.
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="code-block">
<span class="code-keyword">class</span> Student {<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;<span class="code-keyword">String</span> name;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;<span class="code-keyword">int</span> age;<br><br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;<span class="code-keyword">Student</span>(<span class="code-keyword">String</span> name, <span class="code-keyword">int</span> age) {<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<span class="code-keyword">this</span>.name = name;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<span class="code-keyword">this</span>.age = age;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;}<br><br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;<span class="code-keyword">void</span> introduce() {<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;System.out.println(<span class="code-string">"Hi, my name is "</span> + name + <span class="code-string">" and I'm "</span> + age + <span class="code-string">" years old."</span>);<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;}<br>
}<br><br>
Student s1 = <span class="code-keyword">new</span> Student(<span class="code-string">"Helio"</span>, <span class="code-number">20</span>);<br>
s1.introduce();
            </div>

            <div class="breakthrough">
                <h4>üéØ Major Conceptual Shift</h4>
                <p>When I realized that classes are templates for objects, and that constructors are just ways to set up their initial state, everything clicked. Java stopped feeling like random syntax ‚Äî it started feeling like storytelling with logic.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- CONCLUSION -->
        <footer>
            <h2>Reflections on Three Days with an AI Tutor</h2>
            
            <div class="conclusion">
                <h3 style="color: #667eea; margin: 30px 0 15px 0;">What I Discovered</h3>
                
                <div class="analysis-box">
                    <h3>About Learning</h3>
                    <p>I learned that I retain information best when I‚Äôm the one asking the questions ‚Äî AI tutoring encouraged that. It also showed me that I like seeing examples and then trying to remix them. Claude‚Äôs instant feedback made experimentation less scary.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="analysis-box">
                    <h3>About AI Pedagogy</h3>
                    <p><strong>Strengths:</strong></p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Patience and clarity ‚Äî Claude never got frustrated no matter how basic my questions were.</li>
                        <li>Accessibility ‚Äî I could learn at any hour and move at my own pace.</li>
                        <li>Personalization ‚Äî it adjusted examples to fit how I explained things.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p><strong>Limitations:</strong></p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>It lacked awareness of my confusion ‚Äî it only knew when I said I was lost.</li>
                        <li>No emotional encouragement ‚Äî it didn‚Äôt celebrate progress the way a teacher might.</li>
                        <li>Learning felt isolating ‚Äî there was no shared human struggle.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <div class="analysis-box">
                    <h3>Cultural & Ethical Implications</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Access & Equity:</strong> Students with internet access and literacy benefit most ‚Äî AI tutoring still depends on privilege.</li>
                        <li><strong>The Future of Teachers:</strong> I don‚Äôt think teachers will disappear, but they‚Äôll shift into mentors who teach critical thinking and emotional growth.</li>
                        <li><strong>Academic Integrity:</strong> The line between help and cheating depends on intention ‚Äî am I learning or outsourcing my thinking?</li>
                        <li><strong>Learning vs. Performance:</strong> I noticed how easy it is to ‚Äúperform understanding‚Äù by copying working code ‚Äî deep learning requires struggle.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <div class="reflection">
                    <h3>Final Reflection</h3>
                    <p><strong>Would I do this again?</strong> Yes. It gave me confidence to explore topics I‚Äôd otherwise avoid.</p>
                    <p><strong>What I'll miss:</strong> The feeling of collaboration ‚Äî AI doesn‚Äôt laugh with you when your code finally runs.</p>
                    <p><strong>What I gained:</strong> A sense of independence and a clearer mental model of how I learn through questioning.</p>
                    <p><strong>The future:</strong> I think education in 5‚Äì10 years will blend human and AI teaching ‚Äî machines for instant clarity, humans for meaning.</p>
                </div>

                <p style="margin-top: 40px; text-align: center; font-style: italic; color: #666;">
                    This autoethnography documents my lived experience as both subject and researcher,<br>
                    examining the intersection of human learning and artificial intelligence.
                </p>
            </div>
        </footer>
    </div>
